        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText> We break down the technical justification for this project into the following subsections:

Angular resolution:

We propose to observe a 20"x20" region in the M17 star forming region, where we had previously found the lowest levels of turbulence (narrowest spectral line-widths) at the single-dish angular resolution of Li &amp; Houde (2008). We had obtained a turbulent dissipation length scale of L=0.22" (~ 2 mpc) for M17, and used this parameter to calculate the strength of the magnetic field in the plane of the sky for this source. Accordingly, ALMA measurements ranging from the largest structures (20") to the dissipation scale (0.2") would give us two decades of coverage over the power spectrum. This will be essential to observe the transition between the inertial and dissipation ranges. We will be in a position to estimate the ambipolar diffusion scale from the downshift of the ion's velocity dispersion spectrum in the inertial range according to the Li &amp; Houde model, and then directly verify this prediction with our observations in the dissipation range using data at the highest resolution we request, i.e., 0.2". This project thus proposes to make full use of ALMA's power to answer an important 
question about magnetized turbulence.

sensitivity:

We need a high signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) to calculate the velocity dispersions in the spectral line profiles. M17 extends over many arcminutes in the sky and with very few interferometry observations limited to the emission peak only, we can only extrapolate line intensities from our available single-dish data. At the proposed coordinates in M17, we obtained peak line temperatures of 4 K for both HCN and HCO+ (4-3) with the CSO. An rms noise level of 100 mK was sufficiently low to allow such calculations. We intend to map a 20"x20" area, equivalent to the CSO beam size at 356 GHz, at 0.2" resolution. This gives us a map with about 100 grid points. Converting the CSO measurements to Jy/beam units [S(Jy)=50*S(K)], we should expect a peak line temperature of 2 Jy/0.2"beam and rms noise level of 50 mJy/0.2"beam provides a sufficient SNR of 40 for our purpose.

spectral resolution:

Using the Kolmogorov-type power-law functions we obtained for the velocity dispersions (against length scale) for HCN and HCO+ spectra (Li &amp; Houde 2008), we can predict the linewidths of the spectra at 0.2" resolution. For M17, we obtained s[km/s]^2=1.17*L[arcsec]^0.36 for HCN, where "s" is the velocity dispersion (s=FWHM/2sqrt(2ln2)) and L is the length scale. At a scale of 0.2", we expect s=0.8 km/s or a linewidth of FWHM=2 km/s for HCN. HCO+ lines will be narrower, with a lower limit of a thermal width of FWHM=0.22 km/s. 
Since we have one spectral line per baseband and therefore do not need a large bandwidth, we ask for a spectral resolution of 0.026 km/s with a bandwidth of 98 km/s, and smooth the spectra via 8 channel binning to 0.1 km/s. This way, we will avoid high data acquisition rates. 

observing strategy:

The area we intend to observe is almost coverable by the primary beam of ALMA (18" at ~356 GHz), but a single pointing will not be sufficient as we require a uniform sensitivity across the entire region. We thereore ask for a customized mosaic with hexagonal pointing around the central offset position. This adds up to 7 individual pointings, whose offsets are provided above. 

For the 12-m array, we will use the 34-antenna configuration providing  baseline of 1.07 km with a total integration time of 1 hr including calibration and overheads.
We also require 7-m compact array and 12-m total power measurements to observe the transition between the inertial and dissipation ranges, apply the Li &amp; Houde technique, and directly probe the difference between the velocity dispersion spectra of HCN and HCO+ in the energy dissipation range. The OT estimates an additional 30 mins of overhead and calibration time, and a total ACA time of 4 hrs. In total, we ask for 5.43 hours of observing time.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
