    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We aim to use ALMA to probe the turbulent power spectrum and resolve its energy dissipation scale in the M17 molecular cloud. This length scale is typically on the order of a few mpc and is due to the turbulent ambipolar diffusion phenomenon, i.e., the spatial wavelength range where the motions of
ion and neutral species decouple from each other. Importantly, this ambipolar diffusion scale is a measure of the magnetic field strength in the plane of the sky. In a previous study Li &amp; Houde (2008) determined a dissipation length scale of approximately 0.2" (~2 mpc) for M17 using single-dish maps of a pair of coexistent ion and neutral molecules, HCN and HCO+ (J=4-3), and comparing the velocity dispersions stemming from their corresponding spectral lines. We propose to revisit a 20"x20" region in this source, where we found the lowest levels of turbulence (narrowest spectral line-widths) at the single-dish angular resolution of Li &amp; Houde (2008). We aim to use the power of ALMA to cover a range of spatial scales spanning two decades of the turbulent power spectrum, from 20" down to the predicted energy dissipation length scale (i.e., 0.2").  </prp:abstract>
